Currently if you supply a 'plugin' to hock (i.e. mocks defined as a function rather than an oblit) then you end up blowing away the `predefinedMocks`.

Would be nice if it didn't.

```js
var mockRoutes = function(s){
  // get support for responding to same url twice
  s.get("/underscore/-/underscore-1.3.3.tgz").reply(200)
  s.get("/underscore/-/underscore-1.3.3.tgz").reply(200)
}

mr({port: common.port, mocks: mockRoutes}, function (s) {
  // etc
})

// npm test complains of
"Error: No Match For: GET /underscore/latest"

```

When you run `npm-update --save|--save-dev|--save-optional`, all packages that needed updating will magically appear in the section specified by `--save|--save-dev|--save-optional`,  regardless of whether they were originally regular, development or optional dependencies. :-1: .

Example of running `npm update --save` on a simple `package.json` with only a development dependency:

